[00:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Hi. Welcome to another video. So, today I want to talk about a GitHub repo that I think a lot of people are going to overlook at first. Even though it is actually one of the more useful things you can add to your AI coding workflow, it is called Agent'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Skills by Addy Osmani. Now, if you just look at the name, you might think this is another random prompt pack or some little collection of markdown files that sounds smarter than it really is. But, that is not really'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what this is. This repo is basically a structured engineering workflow for AI coding agents, and I think that part matters a lot because the real problem with most coding agents is not that they cannot write code. Most of them can write code just fine. The real problem'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is that they often skip the boring but important parts. They skip clarifying the spec. They skip writing a real plan. They skip proper testing. They skip review discipline. And then, they still act very confident afterwards. So, let\'s'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get right into it. What Addy\'s repo is trying to do is package the workflow of a careful senior engineer into reusable skills that an agent can actually follow. It is not just saying be better. It is saying, here is the process, follow it.'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And that is a huge difference. The repo breaks software work into a real life cycle. Define what to build, plan the work, build it in slices, verify it, review it, simplify where needed, and then ship it. So, instead of'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'treating coding like one giant blob of output, it treats coding like an engineering process with checkpoints. That is already better than how most people use AI coding tools.'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the nice thing is that this is not just one big vague instruction file, either. The repo comes with seven main command entry points that map to the life cycle. So, you have {slash} spec, {slash} plan, {slash} build, {slash} test, {slash}'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'review, {slash} code simplify, and {slash} ship under the hood. Those commands map into a bigger set of skills. There are skills for idea refinement, spec-driven development, planning and task breakdown, incremental'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'implementation, test-driven development, context engineering, API design, front-end work, debugging, review, security, performance, documentation, CI and CD, shipping, and more.'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, this is not a gimmick. It is a pretty serious framework. And what I like about it is that it is opinionated in the right way. It pushes the agent towards specs before code. It pushes small and verifiable'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tasks. It pushes testing as proof instead of testing as an afterthought. It pushes code review before merge. And it pushes simplification instead of cleverness for the sake of it, which is honestly how these tools should work by'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'default. There is also another part here that I think is super important. The repo does not only include the build workflow, it also includes specialist personas like a code reviewer, a test engineer, and a security auditor.'

[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, the idea is not just to make the main agent write code better. It is also to give it structured ways to inspect the code from different perspectives. That is kind of great because a lot of people still use one agent for'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything and hope that it will magically self-correct. But, in practice, separate review mindsets catch different problems. A reviewer catches maintainability issues. A test-focused persona catches missing coverage and weak verification. A security-focused'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one catches things the others may never even look for. So, the repo is really about discipline. It is about process. It is about reducing the dumb failure modes that AI agents still have all the time. Now, another reason I like this'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'repo is that it is not locked into one ecosystem. Yes, it has an official setup story for tools like Claude Code, Cursor, Gemini CLI, WinSurf, Open Code, Copilot, and a few others.'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, the more important point is that these skills are just markdown workflows. They are plain text instructions that agents can follow. So, the value is not really tied to one app. The value is that the workflow is'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'portable. And that is exactly why I think it is interesting for Verdent, too. Before I come to Verdent, though, let me explain how I would think about using this in general. The worst way to use something like this is to dump the whole repo into one giant'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt and hope for the best. I would not do that. The smarter way is to treat it as a life cycle. If I\'m starting something non-trivial, I want the spec-driven development behavior first. Then, I want planning and task'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'breakdown. Then, when code actually starts, I want incremental implementation and test-driven development. Then, before I trust the output, I want code review and quality and maybe security and hardening, too, if the work matters. That is the real'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'power here. It is not about loading more text. It is about loading the right behavior at the right time. And the repo even reinforces that mindset by warning against loading everything at once, which is pretty smart because too much'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'context can be as bad as too little context if it all turns into noise. Now, the pricing side is actually very easy here. The repo itself is free and open source, which is obviously great. So, the real cost is not the skill pack. The real'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cost is whatever agent or model you run it with. If you use it in Claude Code, then your cost is Claude Code. If you use it somewhere else, then your cost is whatever that tool charges. The workflow itself is not the expensive part.'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And that makes it a very nice upgrade because you\'re basically improving agent behavior without adding another subscription layer on top. So, that is pretty good, for sure. Now, let us come to the Verdent angle'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because I know that is what a lot of people here will care about. If you use Verdent, I would not describe this as some exact one-click install in the same way as Claude Code plugin marketplace stuff. That is not really the point. The point is that Verdent already has'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the exact building blocks you would want for something like this. Verdent has global user rules through verdent.md. It has project rules through agents.md. It has plan rules for shaping how'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'planning output looks. It has custom sub-agents, and it has parallel agents with isolated workspaces and get work trees. So, if you ask me, Agent Skills is actually a very natural fit for Verdent. You just have to port the'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workflow in a Verdent native way instead of waiting for some special branded installer. Here\'s how I would do it. First, I would put the always-on behavioral principles into verdent.md if I want them across all projects.'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Things like spec before code, verify changes properly, do not skip testing, prefer simpler solutions, and avoid rationalizing sloppy work. That way, Verdent keeps those preferences with me everywhere. Second, for a specific repo, I would put'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the project-level workflow into agents.md. That is where I would define how I want this particular code base handled. For example, always create a clear spec for anything non-trivial. Always break work'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into small tasks. Always verify with real evidence. Always review before merging. Always keep diffs focused. That is the sweet spot because in Verdent, project rules take priority over user rules. So, if one project has stronger'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'requirements, the project can override the general defaults. Third, I would use Verdent\'s plan rules to shape the planning output. This part is super important because one of the biggest wins from Agent Skills is that it forces the agent to think before'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coding. So, in Verdent plan mode, I would want plans to include scope clarification, acceptance criteria, sequencing, verification steps, and maybe rollback thoughts for riskier changes.'

[07:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That makes the planning stage much more useful. Fourth, I would turn the specialist review personas into custom Verdent sub-agents. This is honestly one of the best fits. You can create a reviewer-style sub-agent, a testing sub-agent, and a'

[07:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'security sub-agent, and then use them deliberately instead of making the main agent pretend to be all three at once. So, for example, after implementation is done, I could ask one Verdent sub-agent to review code quality, another one to'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look specifically for missing tests or weak verification, and another one to scan for security issues. That is a really strong workflow. And then, the fifth part is where Verdent becomes especially interesting, parallel'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workspaces. Because Verdent is very good at running multiple agents with isolated workspaces and get work trees, you can actually map the Agent Skills life cycle onto parallel execution in a way that feels really natural. I would not'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parallelize the spec before the spec exists, obviously. That would be messy. But, once the scope is clear, then this gets really powerful. You can have one workspace implementing the feature. You can have another workspace focused on'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tests and verification. You can have another workspace doing review or trying an alternate implementation. And because Verdent isolates those workspaces, the agents are not constantly stepping on each other. That is super useful. So, instead of'

[08:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thinking, how do I import {slash} spec literally into Verdent, I would think like this. How do I make Verdent behave like {slash} plan before implementation starts? How do I make one workspace behave like {slash} build, another like'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '{slash} test, and another like {slash} review? That is the real adaptation. And to be honest, I think that is better than chasing a superficial one-to-one port because then you\'re using Verdent for what it is actually great at, which'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is orchestration. Now, if I were setting this up in a practical minimal way, I would probably start with just three core pieces from Agent Skills. One, spec-driven development. Two, test-driven development. Three, code review and quality. Those three alone'

[08:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already fix a huge amount of what goes wrong in AI coding workflows. Then, depending on the project, I would selectively add front-end UI engineering, API and interface design, debugging and error recovery, security and hardening, or performance'

[09:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'optimization. So, I would not make Verdent carry all 20 skills at all times. I would keep the core discipline always on, and then load the specialized behavior when the task actually calls for it. That is probably the highest-leverage approach. And by the'

[09:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way, this also matches how good engineers actually work. You do not keep every checklist in your head at maximum intensity at all times. You bring in the right checklist when the work needs it. So, that is great. There is also a bigger takeaway here that I think'

[09:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'matters beyond just this repo. A lot of people still talk about AI coding tools like the model is the whole story. It is not. Model quality matters, obviously, but workflow quality matters, too, maybe even more than people think. A strong'

[09:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model with a sloppy process still produces sloppy outcomes. A decent model with a disciplined workflow can often produce much more reliable work than people expect. And that is why repos like agent skills'

[10:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'matter. They are not trying to magically replace engineering judgment. They are trying to encode it into a reusable operating system for the agent. That is the value. So, my overall take is this. Agent skills is one of the more useful'

[10:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI coding repos out there because it focuses on the thing that actually improves outcomes, which is process, not benchmark hype, not marketing fluff, just better engineering behavior. It gives agents a structured path from idea'

[10:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to shipping. It makes specs matter. It makes planning matter. It makes testing and review harder to skip. And because the skills are plain markdown workflows, the ideas travel well across tools. For Verdin specifically, I think the move is'

[10:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very clear. Use verdin.md for universal habits. Use agents.md for project specific rules. Use plan rules to enforce spec first planning. Use custom sub agents for review, testing, and'

[10:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'security. And use Verdin\'s parallel workspaces to run the life cycle in a more orchestrated way once the scope is already clear. That is a really nice combination. So, yes, I like this a lot. It is free, practical, open source, and'

[11:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it solves a real problem. And if you are already a Verdin user, this is not something you need to ignore just because it was not packaged specifically for Verdin first. If anything, Verdin is one of the better homes for it because Verdin already gives you the rule system'

[11:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and agent orchestration that this kind of workflow wants. Overall, it\'s pretty cool. Anyway, let me know your thoughts in the comments. If you like this video, [music] consider donating through the Super Thanks option or becoming a member by clicking the join button. Also, [music]'

